display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> consists of</fr:em>

    
 <html:ol
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
      
 <html:li
style="list-style-type: &quot;(a) &quot;">
        A <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Z}]]></fr:tex>-module <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H_\mathbb {Z}]]></fr:tex> of finite type, called the "<fr:em>integral lattice</fr:em>";
      </html:li>

      
 <html:li
style="list-style-type: &quot;(b) &quot;">
        A finite increasing filtration <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[W_n]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H_\mathbb {Q}=\mathbb {Q}\otimes _\mathbb {Z} H_\mathbb {Z}]]></fr:tex>, called the <fr:em>weight filtration</fr:em>;
      </html:li>

      
 <html:li
style="list-style-type: &quot;(c) &quot;">
        A finite filtration <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[F^p]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H_\mathbb {C}=\mathbb {C}\otimes _\mathbb {Z} H_\mathbb {Z}]]></fr:tex>, called the <fr:em>Hodge filtration</fr:em>.
      </html:li>

    </html:ol>


    We demand that, on <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H_\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex>, the filtration <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[W_\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> induced by extension of scalars of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[W]]></fr:tex>, the filtration <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex>, and the complex conjugate <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\bar {F}]]></fr:tex> form a system <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(W_\mathbb {C},F,\bar {F})]]></fr:tex> of three opposite filtrations (<fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-ii-1.2.7"
href="hodge-theory-ii-1.2.7.xml"
taxon="Definition"
number="1.2.7" /> and <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-ii-1.2.13"
href="hodge-theory-ii-1.2.13.xml"
number="1.2.13" />).</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
