expanded="true"
root="false"
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1448</fr:anchor><fr:addr
type="user">hodge-theory-ii-2.3.2</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-2.3.2.xml</fr:route><fr:authors /><fr:number>2.3.2</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-ii-2.3</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>We also denote by <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[W]]></fr:tex> the filtration of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H_\mathbb {Z}]]></fr:tex> given by the inverse image of the filtration <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[W]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H_\mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex>.
    The axiom of mixed Hodge structures implies that, for each <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>, the filtration <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex> induces on <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {C}\otimes _\mathbb {Z}\operatorname {Gr}_n^W(H_\mathbb {Z})]]></fr:tex> a filtration that is <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>-opposite to its complex conjugate.
    By <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-ii-2.1.9"
href="hodge-theory-ii-2.1.9.xml"
taxon="Proposition"
number="2.1.9" />, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Gr}_n^W(H_\mathbb {Z})]]></fr:tex> is endowed with a Hodge structure of weight <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>, with Hodge filtration induced by <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
