expanded="true"
root="false"
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1450</fr:anchor><fr:addr
type="user">hodge-theory-ii-2.3.4</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-2.3.4.xml</fr:route><fr:authors /><fr:number>2.3.4</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-ii-2.3</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>A <fr:em>morphism</fr:em> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  H\to  H']]></fr:tex> of Hodge structures is a homomorphism <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  H_\mathbb {Z}\to  H'_\mathbb {Z}]]></fr:tex> that is compatible with the filtrations <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[W]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex> (and thus compatible with <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\bar {F}]]></fr:tex>).
    We immediately deduce from <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-ii-1.2.10"
href="hodge-theory-ii-1.2.10.xml"
taxon="Theorem"
number="1.2.10" /> the following theorem.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
toc="true"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1451</fr:anchor><fr:addr
type="user">hodge-theory-ii-2.3.5</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-2.3.5.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Theorem</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>2.3.5</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-ii-2.3</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
 <html:ol
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
    
 <html:li
style="list-style-type: &quot;(i) &quot;">
      The category of mixed Hodge structures is abelian.
    </html:li>


    
 <html:li
style="list-style-type: &quot;(ii) &quot;">
      The integral lattice of the kernel (resp. cokernel) of a morphism <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  H\to  H']]></fr:tex> is the kernel (resp. cokernel) <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  H_\mathbb {Z}\to  H'_\mathbb {Z}]]></fr:tex>, with <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[K\otimes \mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[K\otimes \mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> being endowed with the induced filtrations (resp. quotient filtrations) of the filtrations <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[W]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H_\mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H_\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> (resp. of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H'_\mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H'_\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex>).
    </html:li>


    
 <html:li
style="list-style-type: &quot;(iii) &quot;">
      Every morphism <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  H\to  H']]></fr:tex> is strictly compatible with the filtration <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[W]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H_\mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H'_\mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex> and with the filtration <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H_\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H'_\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex>.
      It induces morphisms of Hodge <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex>-structures
      <fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[         \operatorname {Gr}_n^w(f)\colon          \operatorname {Gr}_n^W(H_\mathbb {Q})         \to  \operatorname {Gr}_n^W(H'_\mathbb {Q}).       ]]></fr:tex>
      It also induces morphisms
      <fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[         \operatorname {Gr}_F^p(F)\colon          \operatorname {Gr}_F^p(H_\mathbb {C})         \to  \operatorname {Gr}_F^p(H'_\mathbb {C})       ]]></fr:tex>
      that are strictly compatible with the filtration induced by <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[W_\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex>.
    </html:li>


    
 <html:li
style="list-style-type: &quot;(iv) &quot;">
      The functor <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Gr}_n^W]]></fr:tex> is an exact functor from the category of mixed Hodge structures to the category of Hodge <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex>-structures of weight <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>.
    </html:li>


    
 <html:li
style="list-style-type: &quot;(v) &quot;">
      The functor <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Gr}_F^p]]></fr:tex> is an exact functor.
    </html:li>

  </html:ol>
</fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
