xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1454</fr:anchor><fr:addr
type="user">hodge-theory-ii-2.3.8</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-2.3.8.xml</fr:route><fr:authors /><fr:number>2.3.8</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-ii-2.3</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>We define a <fr:em>mixed Hodge <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex>-structure</fr:em> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> to consist of a vector space <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H_\mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex> of finite dimension over <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex>, a finite increasing filtration <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[W]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H_\mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex>, and a finite decreasing filtration <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H_\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex>, with the filtrations <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[W_\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\bar {F}]]></fr:tex> being opposite.
    <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-ii-2.3.5"
href="hodge-theory-ii-2.3.5.xml"
taxon="Theorem"
number="2.3.5" /> generalises trivially to this variation.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
